            <div class="meta">
      <span class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://cps-vo.org/users/admin" title="View user profile.">admin</a> on Wed, 01/16/2013 - 4:40pm</span>
    </div>
        
        <div class="content clearfix">
      <p>The VO collaboration platform is built on top of the open-sourceÂ <a href="http://drupal.org/">Drupal</a>Â content management platform, which powers millions of websites and applications. Itâ€™s built, used, and supported by an active and diverse community of people around the world (including a dedicated <em>Drupal Security Team</em>, which is 40 strong). Â Presently, we use version 6 of the Drupal CMS. Â </p>
<div>Â </div>
<div><img alt="" src="/sites/default/files/u1301/drupalCMS_0.jpg" style="width:500px;height:253px;" /></div>
<div>Â </div>
<div>Within any Drupal installation, there are three primary catagories of information that defines the look, feel, and features provided by the site. Â These categories areÂ <em>code</em>,<em>Â site configuration,Â </em>&amp;Â <em>data</em>. Â  Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
<h2>Code</h2>
<div>The code of your installation defines the fundamental behavior and feature sets provided by the site.</div>
<div>Â </div>
<div><img alt="" src="/sites/default/files/u1301/code.jpg" style="width:600px;height:303px;" /></div>
<div>Â </div>
<p>The architecture, installation, configuration and maintenance of Drupal-based content management systems is well documented atÂ <a href="http://drupal.org/documentation">http://drupal.org</a>, but we summarize the essential ideas here. Â The Drupal architecture is defined by a series of abstraction layers, along with an extensive and well documented <a href="http://api.drupal.org/api/drupal/6">API</a> for extending and modifying default behaviors. Â </p>
<p>Â </p>
<address style="border:0px;font-size:13px;margin:0px 0px 1.385em 80px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;font-family:'Lucida Grande', 'DejaVu Sans', 'Bitstream Vera Sans', Verdana, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:18px;text-align:justify;">"Effective Web design is driven by the need to balance flexibility and simplicity. If a system is too simple, it can only be used for a single purpose - but if it is too flexible, it may be too difficult for new users to learn.</address>
<address style="border:0px;font-size:13px;margin:0px 0px 1.385em 80px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;font-family:'Lucida Grande', 'DejaVu Sans', 'Bitstream Vera Sans', Verdana, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:18px;text-align:justify;">Drupal strives to reconcile these conflicting goals by providing its users with the tools they need to make their own content management solution, while still providing some pre-built components to help them get started. Thus, it can be described both as a content management system (CMS) and a content management framework (CMF) - one system which strives to have the strengths of both, without their deficiencies.</address>
<address style="border:0px;font-size:13px;margin:0px 0px 1.385em 80px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;font-family:'Lucida Grande', 'DejaVu Sans', 'Bitstream Vera Sans', Verdana, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:18px;text-align:justify;">Most CMS's are like a toy boat or truck - specific assumptions have been made about their use, assumptions that would be hard for you to override. Frameworks, on the other hand, provide you with raw materials only - you need to know a programming language and have a clear design vision to put them together.</address>
<address style="border:0px;font-size:13px;margin:0px 0px 1.385em 80px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;font-family:'Lucida Grande', 'DejaVu Sans', 'Bitstream Vera Sans', Verdana, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:18px;text-align:justify;">Drupal is like a Lego kit. Skilled developers have already made the building blocks - in the form of contributed modules - that you need to create a site that suits your needs, whether that is a news site, an online store, a social network, blog, wiki, or something else altogether."<sup><a href="#footnote_drupal_overview">1</a></sup></address>
<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="/sites/default/files/u5/drupal_flow_0.gif" alt="drupal_flow_0.gif" /></p>
<h3>Modules</h3>
<div>A fundamental component of the Drupal Framework is the <em>Modules</em> system. Â Modules are Drupals term for it's plug-n-play extensibility architecture. Â By writing PHP code that conforms to Drupal's documentedÂ API, one may easily extend the core Drupal feature set. Â At the time of this writing, there are approximately 20,000 freely available,Â <a href="http://drupal.org/download">open-source Drupal modules</a>, of which the VO infrastructure relies on approximately 400 modules<a href="#footnote_modules_list"><sup>2</sup></a>Â that were implemented by the open-source community. Â Additionally, there are custom modules implemented by the CPS-VO development team to specifically support the CPS-VO project. Â  As dictated by Drupal's open-source contribution policies, customized installation instructions for each individual module are provided in an includedÂ <em>readme.txt</em>Â file. Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
<h3>Themes</h3>
<div>Similarly, themes are a mechanism for customizing theÂ <em>user interface</em>Â related behaviors of a Drupal-based website. Â The VO collaboration framework includes a single, highly customized theme designed specifically to support the CPS-VO community. Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
<h3>Views</h3>
<div>Finally, in addition to writing customized PHP code, Drupal includes the concept ofÂ <em>Views</em>Â which provide a graphical user interface to system administrators for defining highly complex SQL queries that implement custom report types. Â The VO software infrastructure includes several custom views for generating common, re-usable [typically paramaterized] reports<a href="#footnote_views_list"><sup>3</sup></a>. Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
<h2>Configuration</h2>
<div>In addition to code, which is typically stored within the CPS-VOÂ <a href="http://subversion.apache.org/"><em>Subversion</em></a>Â open-source version control and configuration management system, Â any Drupal installation has custom configuration data that is stored within the site's database tables. Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
<div><img alt="" src="/sites/default/files/u1301/config.jpg" style="width:600px;height:303px;" /></div>
<div>Â </div>
<div>Â </div>
